questions.question: If $$a, b$$ and $$n$$ are natural numbers then $$a^{2n-1}+b^{2n-1}$$ is divisible by
questions.solution:
Let $$P(n)=a^{2n-1}+b^{2n-1}$$

$$P(1)=a+b$$
$$P(2)=a^3+b^3=(a+b)(a^2+b^2-ab)$$
Out of given options we can conclude that $$P(n)$$ is divisible only by $$(a+b)$$

It can also be done by Mathematical Induction.

But here it is objective, so verification is good enough.

questions.question:
Let $$a, b, c$$ and $$d$$ be any four real numbers. Then, $$a^n+b^n=c^n+d^n$$ holds for any natural number $$n$$, if

(This question has some ambiguity, but appeared in WBJEE 2015 exam).
questions.solution:
Option A
$$a+b=c+d$$            ....Given
Squaring on both sides, we get
$$(a+b)^2 = (c+d)^2$$
$$a^2 +b^2 + 2ab = c^2+d^2+2cd$$
$$ herefore a^n+b^n eq c^n+d^n$$


Option B
$$a-b=c-d$$           ...Given
Squaring on both sides, we get
$$(a-b)^2 = (c-d)^2$$
$$a^2 +b^2 - 2ab = c^2+d^2-2cd$$
$$ herefore a^n+b^n eq c^n+d^n$$


Option C
$$a+b=c+d$$              ...(i)
$$a^2+b^2 = c^2+d^2$$    ....(ii)
Consider $$(a+b)^2 = (c+d)^2$$
$$a^2 +b^2 + 2ab = c^2+d^2+2cd$$
$$\Rightarrow 2ab = 2cd$$         ...from (ii) 
$$\Rightarrow ab=cd$$
So, $$a^n+b^n eq c^n+d^n$$ for all $$n  \epsilon N$$.


Option D 
$$a-b=c-d$$              ...(i)
$$a^2-b^2 = c^2-d^2$$    ....(ii)
Consider $$a^2-b^2 = c^2-d^2$$
$$\Rightarrow (a-b)(a+b) = (c-d)(c+d)$$
$$\Rightarrow a+b = c+d$$         ...from (i)       ....(iii)
Adding eq(i) and (ii), we get
$$2a=2c$$
$$\Rightarrow a=c$$
$$ herefore b=d$$          ...from (iii)
So, $$a^n+b^n=c^n+d^n$$ for all $$n  \epsilon N$$.

questions.question:
Consider the following statements
$$P :$$ Suman is brilliant.
$$Q :$$ Suman is rich.
$$R :$$ Suman is honest.
The negation of the statement,
"Suman is brilliant and dishonest if and only if Suman is rich" can be equivalently expressed as :
questions.solution:
Given statement is "Suman is brilliant and dishonest if and only if Suman is rich"
$$\Rightarrow (P\wedge \sim R) \leftrightarrow Q$$
We know that, $$\sim (\ a \leftrightarrow \ b)$$
                      = $$ \sim b \leftrightarrow \ a $$
Thus negation of given statement can be written as -
$$\sim \left((P\wedge \sim R) \leftrightarrow Q\right)$$
$$\sim Q \leftrightarrow (P \wedge \sim R) $$
Hence, option C is correct.

questions.question:
Let
p : Boys are playing
q : Boys are happy
the equivalent form of compound statement of $$\displaystyle p\rightarrow q$$ is
questions.solution:
The equivalent form of the statement $$p \rightarrow q$$ is $$\sim p \vee q$$
On the same lines, the equivalent statement becomes Boys are not playing or they are happy, i.e. option A.

choices.label: A
choices.choice: Boys are not playing or they are happy

choices.label: B
choices.choice: Boys are not happy or they are playing

choices.label: C
choices.choice: Boys are playing or they are not happy

choices.label: D
choices.choice: Boys are not playing or they are not happy

questions.question: The last digit in $$\displaystyle { 7 }^{ 300 }$$ is:
questions.solution:
We go on writing the units digit in the first few terms for the expansion of $$7$$.
$$7^1 \rightarrow 7$$
$$7^2 \rightarrow 9$$
$$7^3 \rightarrow 3$$
$$7^4 \rightarrow 1$$
$$7^5 \rightarrow 7$$
And the terms will keep on repeating.
Thus, the trend repeats itself in multiples of $$4$$.
Since $$300$$ is divisible by $$4$$, the units digit of $$7^{300}$$ would be $$1.$$
